##In Britain, fears grow as foreigners stock up

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

Most Britons were still in the Watch the fires burning across the river when the Italian diagnosis broke into the thousands, and some even joked about the new coronavirus. The social networks that Britons flock to these days are filled with messages praying for God's blessing. Some people joked that foreigners always go to the supermarket behind the Chinese, and they buy whatever the Chinese buy

By Wen Jing, UK based contributing writer for Caijing

Editor | Sun Aimin

No one could have predicted that Britain would end up on the hot list in this way in the global fight against the pandemic. As soon as the policy proposition of "mass immunity" was put forward, both at home and abroad, the cauldron exploded. My husband and I, who have lived in the UK for many years, were well aware of the fragility of the NHS, but we had no idea that in the face of such a powerful virus, there would be an expert who could do such a thing for the government. Recently, many Chinese friends have sent their condolences, wondering what is going on with their Chinese compatriots in the UK? From my own experience, it was a real roller coaster ride around the time of the outbreak.

When the new coronaviruses were diagnosed in Italy at the end of February, when most Britons were still Watch the fires burning across the river, some even joked about the new coronavirus, likening it to corona, a beer that happens to have the same sound, ready to black comedy a magical immunity. Fortunately, the beer company hasn't come out looking for damage to its reputation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Here are some of the things we say about viruses in the UK, both in and around the workplace and on the Internet:

"The last time you had the flu was years ago, Florida -- I was 20 years ago. ".

"This virus is only as deadly as the elderly, and as safe for the young as the young. " -- Are you an expert?

"We British have lived through two World Wars. ".

In contrast to the general coolness of the British, some of the Chinese community in Britain has gone to the other extreme. After all, from the end of December 2019 to February of this year, when China was struggling with an epidemic, overseas Chinese saw too many separations on social media, and videos with family members back home were sobering, warning us to stay home and stock up.

With such vigilance, many Chinese bought masks as soon as they saw the number of confirmed cases in Italy. A Hong Kong friend in the UK bought three cases of face masks at Amazon in late February, sent half of them home and kept half for himself. It was still two for one, about # 6 a pack, less than 50 yuan, which we thought was a bit of an exaggeration. But in a little over a week, Amazon began to limit purchases, requiring a dentist's or special medical certificate, until mid March, when it pulled them all off shelves.

When the single-digit number of confirmed cases in the UK was maintained, the prime minister's Boris Johnson mainly promoted washing hands, sneezing to cover the mouth and singing "happy birthday" twice at a time, without mentioning masks or other measures, maybe to avoid a public panic.

For a long time, in the face of the epidemic, many British people continued to drink beer and sing songs, like a party. The Chinese community worried that it was time to buy hand sanitizer and other disinfectants.

The outbreak is spreading fast

It was not long before the British discovered that the virus and the outbreak were spreading faster than anyone had expected. In just a few days into March, the number of confirmed cases in the UK soared from single-digit to more than 50 in early March.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On March 3rd the British government unveiled a plan of action in four stages: containment, procrastination, research and mitigation. However, less than a week to declare control failure, STRAIGHT INTO THE PROCRASTINATION PHASE! It doesn't feel like phase one is necessary at all. The virus, which had previously been concentrated in London, became increasingly close to our town, and a confirmed case emerged in an area five minutes'drive from our home, where it was a primary school teacher who had been to Italy. There was one death in the only large hospital nearby (around 70 years old) . The number of infections in London, the financial centre, is soaring every day, accounting for about half of all diagnoses in the UK.

We started worrying about the kids, and we planned to get them out of kindergarten. But school teachers and other British parents remain as unfazed as ever. My colleague and I talked about why people in the UK don't wear masks. He said they haven't seen masks since they were children. Doctors and nurses don't even wear masks in clinics.

But the Chinese regardless of these, have put on a mask under great pressure, often by passers-by to look at the complex, every time to go to the supermarket to do a good job of psychological construction: fear of death is not funny, dead is funny.

"If you're smart, you should put on a mask, " he said in a video circulating at the time, after a furious Italian lawmaker was mocked for wearing one in parliament

During that time, my 3 year old went to the emergency room with her head broken. The doctors, nurses and patients in the emergency room were not wearing masks. They were laughing and laughing as usual. One of the nurses had a crazy cough. It was just me and my husband taking turns with the kids standing in the ventilation, away from everyone. To be honest, this contrast is the closest I've come to the word "culture shock. ".

My husband and I decided it was time to stock up. We thought we were moving fast, but the price of rice in London's Chinese supermarkets has gone up rapidly. Some in the Chinese population even buy ice-cream freezers. Her friend's mother-in-law, an Englishman, didn't understand her hoarding behavior until a week later, when the supermarket couldn't even buy hand sanitizer, the British mother-in-law began to worry and went to a far-away supermarket to buy it back and told her, "I went to the supermarket and took the last three bottles of hand sanitizer off the shelf, feeling a little guilty. "

The funniest thing is, there's a rumor out of nowhere that most of the UK's toilet paper is made in China, and it's made out of the same stuff as the masks, and the British soon ran out of toilet paper, so people began to stock up on toilet paper in a frenzy, as if it were a form of global ridicule.

The controversial theory of "group immunity"

On March 13th the British government's chief science officer famously spoke of the concept of herd immunity, which Boris added "we will lose loved ones" . The theory became known as Florida, and the WHO, as well as British medical experts, attacked it, saying that Britain was risking human lives.

The Chinese in the UK are even less relaxed. The immediate effect has been a sudden surge in ticket prices on major airlines, with some even talking of chartered flights to take refuge in their home countries. Our family back home is urging us to return.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(on March 19, CTRIP's one-way economy-class ticket from London to Beijing costs more than 30 hours.)

Speaking like a bucket of cold water, finally woke up some British people, the most immediate change is: more and more British people are also starting to rush to the supermarket; many businesses that need delivery services have started to promote zero-touch delivery (drop-and-go, no physical contact) . Retailers, kindergartens, activity centers and others have written to consumers saying that their stores and work environments have been strictly disinfected to ensure maximum safety and virus isolation.

Some rumors began to spread among the Chinese community. Some said that charter flights were a scam, warning people not to be taken in. Others said that the government was withholding information. There were more real deaths than had been announced. Some began to sell traditional Chinese medicine, there are also many ethnic Chinese being subjected to racial discrimination -- as if a Chinese shop had received a threatening letter attacking them in a vicious and dirty tone, Chinese students being beaten up by foreign children..

The bad news made many Chinese in Britain shudder.

One hundred and eighty degree turn

On March 16th, amid a storm of global anger against the British government, Boris switched gears and issued a stern message to anyone over the age of 70 to insulate themselves at home, while others kept their social distance. Many suspect Boris is a "In order to capture, one must set loose" who feigns inaction to stoke public nerves. True or false, but the effect is quite obvious, the British began to attach importance to epidemic prevention, followed by hoarding all kinds of goods, large and small supermarkets really empty.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
But I don't think Boris is bluffing, because the NHS is chronically short of beds and resources, and there are only eight laboratories in England that can do nucleic acid testing, which is a well known fact, the immediate priority in the UK is to slow the growth curve before the massive number of serious conditions causes the NHS to collapse. According to leaked reports, the government ultimately predicted that 260,000 people would die from the outbreak. His callous remarks may have been a premature showdown.

Take the UK's non emergency medical helpline 111. It usually takes about 20 minutes for the call to be put through, and emergency workers or nurses will answer questions about the underlying condition, mostly as a form of psychological relief, and in serious cases will refer you to a community doctor. Since the outbreak, the government has not allowed suspected patients to go to the hospital on their own, suggesting that they call 111 first. Due to the heavy traffic and lack of manpower, it usually takes 30 minutes to an hour to get through, and many people have given up.

After March 16, the British government announced that patients with mild symptoms of self-isolation at home for 14 days, the hospital can only admit serious cases. The tone of the 111 call changed, the content is disheartening: "If you are mild disease patients, do not have to tell us, please at home isolation. ". If you need quarantine advice, look it up on the website, the phone is not available. Unless your symptoms are severe, you have difficulty breathing and you can't continue your daily routine, you don't need to talk to us."

On March 17, my son had a sudden fever of 103 degrees with a cough that I suspected was common cold, but I was also worried. We called 111 to confirm, and they said that the hospital and the Emergency Room do not admit mild illness, do not do tests, according to our situation, only the child at home isolation. We didn't dare to risk going to the hospital, so we had to stay home. Fortunately, our son's fever soon subsided. We weren't the only ones in a similar situation, feeling helpless and on our own for a split second. Given the medical conditions in the UK, it may be true that the long-lasting stand can only rely on immunity.

Schools are closing

On March 18th Italy recorded a record 475 deaths in a single day, bringing the total death toll in Britain to 104. In anticipation of the closures already in place in Italy, France and Spain, and less than a week after the UK proposed mass immunization, Boris finally announced the closure of all schools in England, it is recommended that private schools and kindergartens also be closed, leaving only a portion of the workforce to care for the children of health care workers, police officers, social workers, delivery drivers and other key personnel, and that free school lunches, which many families desperately need, continue to be provided. It is recommended that people over 70 should be separated from their grandchildren.

The shoe finally dropped. The British Chinese feel a little more at ease. Friends joked that foreigners are now following the Chinese in supermarkets and buying whatever the Chinese buy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(a group of 12 supermarkets across the UK have sent a letter saying they will do their best to ensure the supply of everyday goods.)

Many local employers have contingency plans, including job rotations and some or all of their staff working from home, and London is believed to be close to a full-time Home Office. Many people around us have signed up online as volunteers to deliver daily supplies to isolated elderly people over the age of 70 who live alone. Some supermarkets and pharmacies have opened "special shopping hours" for the elderly to ensure their daily life goes on normally.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(in a YouGov survey of more than 2,000 Britons on March 17th, 41% were still not prepared to stay at home.)

Will closing schools achieve Boris's goal of slowing growth? Has Britain's tardiness cost us our best chance? No one knows the answer.

Before the deadline, the Brits around me still seemed calm, not sure how long that would last. In a significant change, there has been little black comedy of new coronaviruses and outbreaks on British social media in recent days, replaced by messages of prayer for God's mercy.
